						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Great Hierophant wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">When you watch this in 60fps, you can see some that combinations of colors cause the upper left square to visibly flicker, which I thought weird.  I would have lingered longer, but I couldn't see it on the capture device's viewer, so I thought the effect was lost.  When I converted the video to 60fps, it reappeared.</div><br />My captured picture is actually an interlaced image. If you look closely at the top left square, you can see that it is two alternating fields of magenta and yellow, i.e. the output is alternating frames this way.<br /><br />I didn't intend for the capture image to be a thing to verify your emulators against, just a sample image demonstrating some of the colour artifacts that can be produced. For instance, the edges of white text via the capture card show a lot of rainbow stripes there, but a different decoder, like the one in my TV, produces much cleaner definition on that. A lot of this stuff varies significantly from device to device. (Also don't forget there are 6 possible alignments of the PPU!)</div>

